Market timing under public and private information

A. Chernulich (NYU Abu Dhabi), J. Horowitz (BSU), J.P. Rabanal (Monash U), O. Rud (RMIT University), M. Sharifova (U.Pacific)

motivation

  • forecast when stocks outperform bonds [Henriksoon and Merton, 1981].

  • public: index funds, stock market.

  • empirical studies focus on stock market participation.

  • what happen when information is private?

  • private: real investment, hedge funds, venture capital.

design

  • stock return at time \(t\) is \(x_t\)

  • \(x\) follows autoregressive process AR(1)

  • bond yields a payoff \(r_f\)

  • people demand information (bandit problems) or avoid it (ostrich effect)

conclusion

  • demand for information overcomes risk and loss aversion.

  • Higher level of participation in private information –> information disclosure policies.
